Roman Shipwrecks network

Antonio Rivero Ostoic

CEDHAR, Aarhus University

jaro@cas.au.dk

22 februar 2022

This post concerns the Strauss shipwrecks database on Roman Shipwrecks network:

Strauss, J. (2013). Shipwrecks Database. Version 1.0. Accessed (07-12-2021) from oxrep.classics.ox.ac.uk/databases/shipwrecks_database/

Built from Parker, A.J. Ancient Shipwrecks of the Mediterranean and the Roman Provinces (Oxford: BAR International Series 580, 1992)

Shipwrecks Database

Andrew Wilson coordinates a catalogue of all known ancient wrecks in the Mediterranean up to 1500 AD where there is the database from Julia Strauss’s PhD thesis Roman Cargoes: Underwater Evidence from the East (London 2007).

Requirements

Install and load R packages to run the code snippets.

# v0.7.4 or higher
library("sdam") 
library("readxl") # read MS Excel sheets
library("networkD3") # plot interactive graphs
# v2.9.8 or higher
library("multiplex")
library("multigraph") # plot valued directed graphs

Retrieving the Data

The Shipwrecks Database is distributed as a ZIP filesystem that needs a temporal file where to download it. The workflow below gives the steps in R with credits to this discussion.

temp <- tempfile()
download.file("http://oxrep.classics.ox.ac.uk/docs/StraussShipwrecks.zip", temp)

Next, we make the connection with the temporal file and unzip it with the "utils" package into object con, and because StraussShipwrecks is an MS Excel file with different sheets, we use package "readxl" to recursively read the excel sheets.

# connect temporal file and unzip excel file
con <- utils::unzip(temp, "StraussShipwrecks.xlsx")
# recursively read Excel sheets
allsheets <- sapply(readxl::excel_sheets(con), simplify=FALSE, USE.NAMES=TRUE,
            function(z) readxl::read_excel(con, sheet = z))

Before continuing with the analysis, however, we need to close the connections and remove unused files.

# close connection and garbage collection
CatchupPause <- function(Secs){
 Sys.sleep(Secs) # pause to let connection work
 closeAllConnections()
 gc()
}
# close also with temporal file
unlink(temp)

Analysis

We start by looking at this database with the "base" summary() function.

# content in the excel sheets
summary(allsheets)
           Length Class  Mode
Shipwrecks 35     tbl_df list
Amphorae    5     tbl_df list

Where we can see that actually the database contains two datasets, Shipwrecks and Amphorae, which are components having 35 and 5 variables, respectively. Also notice that package "readxl" stores these two data frames with a tibble flavour.

Timespans of Existence

Use function plot.dates() from package "sdam" to plot the timespans of existence of the shipwrecks that are in variables 'Earliest date' and 'Latest date'.

# plot shipwrecks timespans
sdam::plot.dates(sw, taq="Earliest date", tpq="Latest date")

Shipwrecks timespans of existence

Alternatively, plot with plot.dates() using the two IDs existing in the dataset, which are Wreck ID and Strauss ID.

# use Wreck ID
plot.dates(sw, id="Wreck ID", 
           taq="Earliest date", tpq="Latest date")

# use Strauss ID
plot.dates(sw, id="Strauss ID", 
           taq="Earliest date", tpq="Latest date")

Sea Areas

The shipwrecks dataset has geographical information to produce networks of relations with possible trajectories of the Roman ships. These variables are the Sea area of the shipwreck together with the network data in Place of origin and Place of destination that are columns 5, 20 and 21 in object sw.

sw[ ,c(5,20:21)]

There are, however, that some record entries need cleaning from question marks, spaces, lower/upper cases, etc. Below, we look at some examples in the dataset, and use functionalities in the "sdam" internal function cln() that removes special characters and capitalizes words to uniform the data as much as possible for further analyses.

# four entries to clean
sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)]
# A tibble: 4 x 3
  `Sea area`            `Place of origin` `Place of destination`       
  <chr>                 <chr>             <chr>                        
1 Adriatic              Rhodes            northern Italy               
2 Tyrrhenian Sea        Aegean.           Rome                         
3 Aegean                Cos?              Black Sea?                   
4 Eastern Mediterranean Tripolitania (?)  Brega, for trans shipment (?)
# default clean
sdam::cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)])
               Sea area Place of origin         Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes               northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea         Aegean.                         Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                    Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean Tripolitania () Brega, for trans shipment ()
# include specific characters
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], what=c("(",")"))
               Sea area Place of origin       Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes             northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea         Aegean.                       Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                  Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean   Tripolitania  Brega, for trans shipment 
# raise level for dots and spaces at the end
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], level=2, what=c("(",")"))
               Sea area Place of origin      Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes            northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea          Aegean                      Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                 Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean    Tripolitania Brega, for trans shipment
# also capitalize words
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], level=2, what=c("(",")"), case=1)
               Sea area Place of origin      Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes            Northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea          Aegean                      Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                 Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean    Tripolitania Brega, For Trans Shipment

The first option removes only characters ?*+, and the second one removes also parenthesis. The command with a raised "level" removes also unnecessary spaces and dots at the end of each record, and 1 in "case" implies capitalization of just the first letter in each word.

Network Relations

The places of origin and destination recorded in the Strauss shipwrecks dataset allows us producing a network representation of the possible trajectories of the Roman ships, and this information constitutes one kind of relation in a broader transportation system.

Edge List and Adjacency Matrix

In order to produce the network, we create first an edge list object called edgel with the two network variables in sw cleaned with the cln() options showed above and a column 't' for indicating the network ties.

# clean and remove NA entries
edgel <- cln(sw[ ,20:21], level=2, what=c("(",")"), case=1, na.rm=TRUE)
# head and tail of edge list
rbind(head(edgel), tail(edgel))
                   Place of origin      Place of destination
1                            Egypt            Northern Italy
2                              Cos            Northern Italy
3                           Rhodes            Northern Italy
4                           Aegean            Northern Italy
6                           Rhodes            Northern Italy
7                           Aegean            Northern Italy
1740             Herakleia Pontica                    Bizone
1754                       Baetica                      Rome
1755                     Lusitania                      Rome
1756 Southern Spain Via Marseilles                      Pisa
1759     Southern Levant Or Cyprus Southern Levant Or Cyprus
1765         Central Western Italy                    Aegean

Uses function transf() from "multiplex" to transform the edge list into the adjacency matrix of the network in array mat.

# construct matrix from edge list assuming one relation
mat <- multiplex::transf(edgel, type="toarray")
# size of matrix
dim(mat)
[1] 143 143

Graph Representation

We plot the Roman Shipwrecks network as a directed graph using a force-directed layout algorithm with R package "multigraph" and different options that allows seeing the many components in the network.

# plot customized graph
multigraph::multigraph(mat, layout="force", seed=3, ecol=4, col="#C0C0C0", vcol0=7, pos=0, fcol=8, rot=45)

Graph for Strauss Roman Shipwrecks network.

Plotting with "networkD3"

"networkD3" is an R package popular for producing Sankey diagrams, and which uses the capabilities of "htmlwidgets" package. It has function simpleNetwork() to be able to plot networks as ‘D3 JavaScript’ network graph allowing interactivity through a web browser. Plotting the sea regions in the Roman Shipwrecks network with this function, however, needs a data frame class object with the edge list as the input network.

To convert the ties recorded in matrix mat into an edge list format, we use transf() again but now with the "toedgel" option in the 'type' argument where edgel carries the edge list. Since some labels in mat have names separated by a comma followed by space or ,, which is the default separator of the function, we specify a tab separator in 'sep' to avoid breaking labels.

# edge list from adjacency matrix
elmat <- transf(mat, type="toedgel", sep="\t")

and look at the head of the edge list data frame

head(elmat)
                                   s             r t
1         Adriatic-Brindisi-Campania   Gaul, Spain 1
2 Adriatic Via Africa, Spain, France          Pisa 1
3                           Adriatic        Aegean 1
4                           Adriatic        Aegean 1
5                           Adriatic    Alexandria 1
6                           Adriatic Cyprus/Levant 1
Interactive Graphs

Now we can plot the sea regions in the Roman Shipwrecks network with simpleNetwork() from "networkD3" using the 'zoom' and other options to see the graph structure more easily.

# zoom into a simple undirected network
networkD3::simpleNetwork(elmat, fontFamily="sans-serif", opacity=1, zoom=TRUE)

Sea regions in Roman Shipwrecks network.

And same steps to plot the network largest component as interactive graph without zoom.

Notice that there is an isolated entity in the network; however, this is another component in the Roman Shipwrecks network having a self-relationship.

require("magrittr")
mat %>% 
  multiplex::bundles(loops=TRUE) %>% 
  multiplex::summaryBundles() %>% 
  tail(4)
                                                          Bundles
Loop1                                       o{R} (Cyprus, Cyprus)
Loop2                                         o{R} (Italy, Italy)
Loop3                                               o{R} (NA, NA)
Loop4 o{R} (Southern Levant Or Cyprus, Southern Levant Or Cyprus)

Part of the exploratory network analysis is to look at the dyadic relations in the system, particularly if is directed like the Roman Shipwrecks network. The two functions from "multiplex" used above serve to find the different bundle patterns occurring in the network.

Largest component

We focus on the network largest component that is the second component in the output of comps() above. By selecting this component with argument 'sel' in function rel.sys(), we obtain the adjacency matrix as an array 'type' object that is recorded in matc with has 95 nodes.

# adjacency matrix of selected largest component
matc <- multiplex::rel.sys(mat, type="toarray", sel=comps(mat)$com[[2]])
# matrix size
dim(matc)
[1] 95 95

Then plot the largest component in the Roman Shipwrecks network where locations and their connections are easier to see.

Plotting largest component of sea regions with "multigraph":

# graph of largest component with adjusted vertex-edge distance
multigraph(matc, loops=TRUE, layout="force", cex=3, col=8, vcol0=7, lwd=3, ecol=4, pos=0)

Directed graph of largest component in Roman Shipwrecks network.

Plotting largest component of sea regions with "networkD3":

# largest component 
simpleNetwork(transf(matc,type="toedgel",sep="\t"), fontFamily="sans-serif", opacity=1)

Interactive graph of largest component in Roman Shipwrecks network.

Seas in Mediterranean Basin

All locations in the two network variables of the edge list in edgel, which are Place of origin and Place of destination, belong to a certain sea or region in the Mediterranean Basin or neighbouring waters. One could use information from the Sea area variable in sw; however, this variable corresponds to the shipwreck locations, which in many cases are far from the origin and destination of the ship.

The following characters serve to discern clusters of origin and destination places within Strauss Roman Shipwrecks network where most sea names are in D. Hessong cartographical map (2001).

  • A or Æ: Aegean, including Minoan Sea
  • D: Adriatic Sea
  • I: Ionian Sea, including Ausonian Sean and Messenian Sea
  • T: Tyrrhenian Sea
  • B: Baetica, including Alboran/Iberian Sea
  • L: Ligurian Sea, including Baleares
  • E: East, from Cilician Strait through Levante Basin
  • F: Africa, including Libyan Sea and Cyrene
  • P: Punic Sea, including Berber Sea
  • C: Black Sea
  • G: Gaul
  • X: India

Because some locations entries in this dataset are vague, the clustering information for the places of origin and destination for the reduction of the network result ambiguous with entries having more than one letter.

The assignation of Sea Regions to the places of origin and destination was made by hand and are recorded in a tabular separated table in file ShipwreckSeas.txt. To load this file into object ss we need to specify the separator of the data that in this case has a header.

# read file with Mediterranean sea regions per place
ss <- read.table(file="ShipwreckSeas.txt", header=TRUE, sep="\t")

An excerpt of ss given below illustrates the location ambiguity in the data. For instance, Aegean And Italy in entry 8 imply three possible region seas that are Aegean, Ionian, and Adriatic; however, Aegean Rome in entry 10 implies the west coast of the Italian peninsula. In this case, the sea region corresponds to the Tyrrhenian Sea rather than the east coast facing the Adriatic.

# excerpt with 9 sea regions
ss[8:16,]
                        PLACE  CODE
8            Aegean And Italy A,D,I
9    Aegean And Lastly Cyprus   A,E
10                Aegean Rome A,T,I
11  Aegean Tripolitania Italy A,D,I
12            Aegean Via Cosa     A
13  Aegean Via Southern Italy   A,I
14              Aegean, Italy A,D,I
15              Aegean/Africa   A,F
16 Aegean/N. Africa/Propontis   A,F

Network Reduction

A clustering information serves to reduce the network into related sets of equivalent places in the system.

# matching sea regions to the edge list
ss[c(head(match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),3), tail(match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),3)),]
                            PLACE CODE
73                          Egypt    E
60                            Cos    A
137                        Rhodes    A
153 Southern Spain Via Marseilles    B
152     Southern Levant Or Cyprus    E
53          Central Western Italy    T

Then we create a newdata frame edgelc with sea region codes in ss, which are in columns from and to.

# data frame with codes
edgelc <- cbind(edgel, from=ss[match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),]$CODE, 
                       to=ss[match(edgel[,2], ss$PLACE),]$CODE)
# look at first entries
head(edgelc)
  Place of origin Place of destination from  to
1           Egypt       Northern Italy    E L,D
2             Cos       Northern Italy    A L,D
3          Rhodes       Northern Italy    A L,D
4          Aegean       Northern Italy    A L,D
6          Rhodes       Northern Italy    A L,D
7          Aegean       Northern Italy    A L,D

Sea Regions Origin and Destination

The adjacency matrix of letters in mat0 comes from columns from and to in edge list edgelc and are located in column positions 3 and 4.

# ties in sea regions
mat0 <- transf(edgelc[,3:4], type="toarray")

and then plot the multigraph of the reduced structure.

# list of characteristics
scp <- list(valued=TRUE, loops=TRUE, cex=3, pos=0, ecol=4, col=8, vcol0=7, alpha=c(1,.5))

# force-directed with random seed
multigraph(mat0, scope=scp, layout="force")

Sea regions in the Roman Shipwrecks network as valued graph.

To plot the reduced structure with simpleNetwork() from "networkD3" on an edge list from its adjacency matrix.

simpleNetwork(transf(mat0,type="toedgel"), fontFamily="sans-serif", opacity=1)

Sea regions simple plot.
